  <static seed="65" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FractionArithmetic/AddFractions50.pg">
    <statement><p>Add: <m>\displaystyle{-\frac{1}{8} + \frac{29}{48}}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="11" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{23}{48}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To add two fractions with different denominators, we first have to find a common denominator. In this case, the least common multiple of <m>8</m> and <m>48</m> is <m>48</m>.</p>
<p>Look at the first fraction <m>\displaystyle{-\frac{1}{8}}</m>. To change the denominator to <m>48</m>, we multiply <m>6</m> at both the top and bottom, and we have:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \begin{aligned}-\frac{1}{8} \amp = -\frac{1 \cdot 6}{8 \cdot 6}\\ \amp = -\frac{6}{48} \end{aligned}}</m></p>
<p>The second fraction already has the common denominator.</p>
<p>Finally, we can do the addition. The full process is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   -\frac{1}{8} + \frac{29}{48}
        \amp = -\frac{6}{48} + \frac{29}{48} \\
        \amp = \frac{-6 + 29}{48} \\
        
        \amp = \frac{23}{48}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
</solution>
